    "Transcript": [
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:00:00",
            "end_time": "00:00:31",
            "text": "Hello, hey guys, welcome to Concept and Coding and today at Daily DSA Practice channel this is the first mock with Jagannath. Welcome Jagannath to this mock interview. Are you ready?"
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:00:32",
            "end_time": "00:00:36",
            "text": "Yeah, yeah."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:00:37",
            "end_time": "00:01:03",
            "text": "Before starting, I want to confirm that I will be uploading this on YouTube. You do not have any concern, right?"
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:01:04",
            "end_time": "00:01:07",
            "text": "Yeah, okay."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:01:08",
            "end_time": "00:01:28",
            "text": "Before starting it, can you just give a brief about yourself?"
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:01:29",
            "end_time": "00:02:05",
            "text": "My name is Chivukula Jagannath. I graduated in 2022 from an IT center, and currently I am working as an engineer at Samsung, Noida."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:02:06",
            "end_time": "00:02:24",
            "text": "Awesome. You have around six months of experience?"
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:02:25",
            "end_time": "00:02:27",
            "text": "Yeah."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:02:28",
            "end_time": "00:03:03",
            "text": "This will be around a 40 minute round. I have one DSA question for you. If you have any pad or editor where you can write code, please share your screen."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:03:04",
            "end_time": "00:03:16",
            "text": "Yeah, sure. I think you are able to see my screen now."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:03:17",
            "end_time": "00:03:30",
            "text": "Yes, I am able to see your screen. Please open any pad where you want to write."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:03:31",
            "end_time": "00:04:35",
            "text": "The question is: you are given a list of integers. The order of elements will be increasing and then decreasing. You have to find the peak. For example, for 1, 3, 6, 4, 2, 0, first it increases to 6 and then decreases, so the output should be 6. Are you clear with the question?"
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:04:36",
            "end_time": "00:05:03",
            "text": "Yeah. I have one clarification. Is it guaranteed that the answer will exist?"
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:05:04",
            "end_time": "00:05:29",
            "text": "Yes, if values are present, definitely there will be a peak."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:05:30",
            "end_time": "00:05:58",
            "text": "For example, if the array is strictly increasing or strictly decreasing, then the peak would be the last or first element respectively?"
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:05:59",
            "end_time": "00:06:28",
            "text": "Correct. If it is totally decreasing like 4, 3, 2, 1, then peak would be 4. If the array is empty, output should be minus 1."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:06:29",
            "end_time": "00:06:41",
            "text": "Okay. I will code in C++. Is it okay?"
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:06:42",
            "end_time": "00:06:47",
            "text": "Yes, totally okay."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:06:48",
            "end_time": "00:08:50",
            "text": "Let me take an example: 1, 3, 6, 2, 1, 0. It is increasing and then decreasing, so one part of the array is sorted and the remaining part is reverse sorted. I think I can use binary search. If I take start and end, the mid element may be 6. I will compare mid with mid plus 1. If mid is greater than mid plus 1, then mid plus 1 to end is on the right side of the peak, so the answer may exist on the left. I will take end as mid. If mid is less than mid plus 1, peak is to the right, so start becomes mid plus 1."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:08:51",
            "end_time": "00:09:20",
            "text": "Can you zoom in a little bit so whoever sees it can read what you are writing?"
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:09:21",
            "end_time": "00:09:32",
            "text": "Sure, control plus should work. Thanks."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:09:33",
            "end_time": "00:09:56",
            "text": "Are you sure you are not missing any edge cases?"
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:09:57",
            "end_time": "00:10:08",
            "text": "I will look at the edge cases while writing at the end."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:10:09",
            "end_time": "00:11:15",
            "text": "What about duplicates? For example 1, 3, 7, 6, 6, 6, 4, 3, 2, 1, or 1, 3, 6, 6, 6, 7, 4, 3, 2, 1. In both cases, your mid may come as 6 where its left and right are both 6. The peak will be 7. How will you handle that?"
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:11:16",
            "end_time": "00:12:08",
            "text": "Okay, I did not consider duplicates. If mid is equal to mid plus 1, then I am not sure whether the answer is on the right or left. I may need to skip elements."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:12:09",
            "end_time": "00:12:43",
            "text": "Your binary search direction is correct. You just need to enhance the solution. Think about when you need to go left, when to go right, and when to search both sides."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:12:44",
            "end_time": "00:13:56",
            "text": "The brute force solution would be to traverse the whole array, initialize answer to minimum, update it with the maximum value, and return it. That takes O(n). It can be improved because the array has an increasing part and a reverse sorted part, so binary search should be possible. But I need to handle the equal case."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:13:57",
            "end_time": "00:14:46",
            "text": "Let us come up with the approach first before coding. What is your first condition?"
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:14:47",
            "end_time": "00:15:32",
            "text": "First, if element at mid is greater than element at mid plus 1, then the possible answer can be found from start to mid."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:15:33",
            "end_time": "00:15:52",
            "text": "Okay. And the second condition?"
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:15:53",
            "end_time": "00:16:42",
            "text": "If mid is less than mid plus 1, then the answer exists from mid plus 1 to end. I will set start to mid plus 1."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:16:43",
            "end_time": "00:17:38",
            "text": "Now handle the case where mid equals mid plus 1 or the neighboring values are equal due to duplicates."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:17:39",
            "end_time": "00:18:32",
            "text": "If mid is equal to mid plus 1 and mid minus 1 is also equal to mid, then I cannot decide. I will need to search both sides and take the maximum."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:18:33",
            "end_time": "00:20:02",
            "text": "Exactly. In the normal case, if mid plus 1 is greater than mid, the peak is on the right. If mid minus 1 is greater than mid, the peak is on the left. If duplicates make it impossible to decide, search both sides."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:20:03",
            "end_time": "00:21:46",
            "text": "So for the duplicate case, if mid equals mid plus 1 and mid minus 1 also equals mid, I will search from start to mid minus 1 and from mid plus 1 to end, then return the maximum of those answers."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:21:47",
            "end_time": "00:22:12",
            "text": "Correct. Go ahead with that approach and code it."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:22:13",
            "end_time": "00:25:20",
            "text": "I will write a function to find the peak. It will take the vector and return the index where the peak is present. I will initialize start to 0 and end to n minus 1. While start is less than end, I will calculate mid. If nums[mid] is greater than nums[mid + 1], I set end to mid. Else if nums[mid] is less than nums[mid + 1], I set start to mid + 1. For equality, I will recursively search the left and right ranges and return whichever gives the larger value."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:25:21",
            "end_time": "00:25:42",
            "text": "You are almost there. Continue and also think about boundary handling."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:25:43",
            "end_time": "00:27:42",
            "text": "I need to handle empty array by returning minus 1. For mid plus 1 and mid minus 1, I need to ensure the indices do not go out of bounds. If the recursive calls return valid indices, I will compare their values. If start equals end, that index can be returned."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:27:43",
            "end_time": "00:28:32",
            "text": "What would be the time complexity of this approach?"
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:28:33",
            "end_time": "00:29:02",
            "text": "If there are no duplicates, it will be O(log n). If there are duplicates, I think it may be O(log n) plus O(log n)."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:29:03",
            "end_time": "00:30:05",
            "text": "Consider all elements equal, like 2, 2, 2, 2, 2. Every time you would go left and right. Ultimately you would traverse each element at least once. So worst case is O(n), and best case is O(log n)."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:30:06",
            "end_time": "00:30:25",
            "text": "Okay, yes, in the worst case it becomes O(n)."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:30:26",
            "end_time": "00:30:48",
            "text": "We are almost at time. Shall we go for feedback?"
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:30:49",
            "end_time": "00:31:04",
            "text": "Yeah, no problem."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:31:05",
            "end_time": "00:31:18",
            "text": "Before the feedback, any feedback for me? Were the questions clear or was I in a hurry?"
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:31:19",
            "end_time": "00:31:42",
            "text": "No, it was good. It is a great initiative that you are giving mock interviews for free."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:31:43",
            "end_time": "00:34:47",
            "text": "Here are a few things. First, the good parts: you looked confident, you kept smiling, and it seemed like you were enjoying the interview. You initially tried to identify edge cases, and you were thinking out loud throughout the process. You also asked for hints when you got stuck, which is good because in interviews time is limited. Areas to improve: you missed the important duplicate use case at the beginning. In interviews, simple-looking questions often hide such tricky cases, so clarify them before coding. Also, the brute force approach should be stated first, then move to the optimized approach. Your coding looked fine, but use proper method and variable names. Avoid names like BS or idx; write code as if it is production quality. Overall, this was a medium-level question. With a little more practice, you will improve further."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Chivukula Jagannath",
            "start_time": "00:34:48",
            "end_time": "00:35:03",
            "text": "Okay, thank you."
        },
        {
            "Speaker Name": "Shrayansh Jain",
            "start_time": "00:35:04",
            "end_time": "00:35:19",
            "text": "Good luck, Jagannath. Bye."
        }
